fields.comments: Garcia played the opening notes of Jack Straw
Weir ends it playing the Cryptical riff
The Bach Arrangement after second verse
The band is undecided on what to play but Hornsby plays Dear Prudence
Weir scat singing on outtro jam.
was going into China Doll but guitars went out of tune and they stopped.
Alternate lyrics during third and fourth verse
No Bass intro. Bob sings first verse without drums.
Bob starts playing One More Saturday Night but Jerry plays Good Lovin'
Weir “We’re gonna beg your indulgence and do another semi-slow song but it won’t stay slow forever.”
They did not incorporate the ending part of the segue
The first time Weir sings The Sun's Gonna Shine
DP10 denoted this as "Playing Jam". That is not a stretch but to call it Playing would set an odd precedent throughout. Deadlists oddly denoted it as "space"
Weir plays the theme to James Bond warming up
arguably one of the greatest stretches
Funiculi Funicula played as warm up. Weir was playing Looks Like Rain
Weir sings 'We can share the women, we can share the wine, one more time.'
Get Back Truckin' On 7 - "Busted!" Crowd reaction due to Garcia's drug bust earlier in the year.
Garcia doing same style of playing as he did on 4/30/77 Improv
Garcia plays the head of So What warming up
Featuring John Belushi on vocals during chorus
First time it goes into Estimated
In reference to Sugaree having the tempo pushed, Weir states, "We’re gonna take a moment to tune up while the rhythm section gets a grip of themselves."
Lesh mistakenly plays the Other One riff at the start of song.

Weir states, “This next set is respectfully dedicated to all the little mice and rats who are traps in laboratories all over the world. And also to the keepers of the peace up on that building over there with their cameras and binoculars and all that kinda stuff. Looking out for your best interest.
Weir says, “For the show we decided to come as a six-pack.”
Weir sings a verse from "I Ain't Superstitious'
Garcia started in with Other One
‘Ever she went an had her sex changed’; Get Back Truckin' On - 7 times. Whistle blow opening.
5 beats. Weir referencing the botched transition says, "Just like a Swiss watch."
‘Ever since she went an had her sex changed’
Lyrics to 'Iko Iko' sung at start.
No Bass intro; Weir vocals with Sound Effects.
'ever since she had a little sex change. All I say it ain't the same.' Jerry laughs. Get back Truckin' on! 7 Times.

Weir states before Casey Jones encore, "On this date eighty one years ago there was a train wreck not too far from here and the engineer of the train died but his memory lives." Casey Jones was killed April 30, 1900.
@3:34 mark Garcia plays his horrible signature scale riff.
Weir says "I don't know how many of you know that today is Ho Chi Minh's birthday. It's true. I read it in my alamanc."
in segue way Garcia starts with the scale riff.
Weir says, "Thank you. We are going to do a song of social import."
The band started with Wharf Rat
During ending 'Not Fade Away' vamp Weir implores crowd, "You got to sing now!"
whistle blow opening. Get Back truckin on 7 times

Lesh says, “While we are testing our monitors there might be something that can be said about trying to be nice to this place. In other words, don’t stand on the seats or kick in the walls or rip out the ornaments seeing how this is the only place we’d like to play around here. And if we can’t come here back to this theatre we won’t come to back to this town, which means you’ll have to go to Kiel auditorium and listen to ‘Grand Funk Railroad’. So consider it”  Weir says, "Now ladies and gentlemen, here they are straight from Madison Square Gardens and famous New York - The Grateful Dead"  Get Back Truckin’ On!  7 times.
Weir playing China Cat Sunflower riff.
From 6:58 to 09:10 Band playing along with the crowd chant
Lesh says, "whomever is throwing all those firecrackers especially up on stage why don't you go on to a Ted Nugent concert instead of here so why don't y'all gone on home, ok?"
Noted Rock critic Robert Christgau described this performance as "creaky and transcendent".
Brent sings a verse of Dear Mr. Fantasy
Weir before Jack Straw, "This place got mice."
*with Ken Kesey and the Thunder Machine
Weir prior to Sugar Mag, "Of course, we need a big hand for the Merry Pranksters on the Thunder Machine." No Sunshine Daydream.
Flanger effect on vocals during breakdown. After Wharf Rat are 56 seconds of directionless playing concluding on what to play next.
Weir says, "Welcome to the Rock n' Roll barbeque."
Technically, this show was played as one set but clearly divided into the 2 set format. Weir says, "Don't nobody catch a cold out there." referencing the 100 degree heat.
Show billed as, "Mickey Hart & His Heartbeats" and underneath in smaller type "Bobby Ace & His Cards From The Bottom Of The Deck."
Garcia, at end of Candyman. "This is an electric guitar."
Garcia, before start of Cumberland says, "Something new." At the prompt of hearing feedback Weir says, "That's the Bear solo."
Garcia says, "Hey Where's Pig? Where gonna have Pig Pen come out and do some tunes. That is if we can find him."
Garcia says, "Pig Pen is going do something."
Garcia doing that scale riff during end jam

At the end of this improv, one of the drummers is continually playing. However, we do not consider this anything other than passing the time. You can hear the band members discussing what to play next.
we do not count this transition as intentful
Whistle Intro, Get Back Truckin' On 8 times
Presuming Jerry left stage to deal with his laryngitis.
It trailed off into Smokestack Lighting' Jam before going into Terrapin
Weir, "ever since she went and had all her pets changed." Get back Truckin' On 7 times
Ever since she went and had her sex change. Get Truckin' Back On 8 Times
Bob sings, "Little Star" with mic volume off
Weir started with One More Saturday Night
Birds chirping and singing sound effects
Weir before song, "This is only a test."
Weir, "It's Polka time, ladies and gentleman!"
Lesh, "This is a sensitive song about all sorts of things."

Weir says, "...we are not all that late anyway. The news is circulating backstage that we will be going on soon and pretty soon the whole band will be here. Donna says, "Calling Doctor Beachwood, Doctor Beachwood calling Doctor Shot, Doctor Shot. You're needed on he stage please. Assistance on the stage please."

Weir says, "We are getting everything just exactly right. I don't know if you are going to understand this any better than I do but Mickey wanted me to inform you in his opinion, "The first law of rock n roll is drummers do not make house calls". I don't understand either.
Whistle blowing opening; Get Back Truckin' On

Weir says, "I'd like a show of hands. It's a simple question: How many of you out there have ever seen a gorilla play a piano? More than one you expect! I've never seen a gorilla play a piano. Not for the squeamish."
appears on Reckoning. This next number is a drummer's choice.
whistle blow opening; Get Back Truckin' On  7 times
Weir says, "Tomorrow's Sunday, we're not gonna be here, so we're going to take advantage of today to give you some inspirational words of advice."
There was a full stop after El Paso. They did not go into another jam but they did return to a jam.
Weir and Garcia play the China Cat during one section.
Ending jam on main riff not played
"It's a rotten stinkin' fucking shame!" Get back Truckin' On: 7 Times
after 4:53 the dynamic of the jam changes.
first verse sung with no drums

After the song, Weir says, "We've been friends with Carlos Santana for a long time and just to prove it, we're gonna invite him out and see if he remembers this tune like we do. Or if we even remember it."
Afterwards, Weir says, "We're gonna do a tune we did last night. On account we need to do it again because we need to practice."
At the 6:23 mark there is a 15 second drum break
Phil plays Fire On The Mountain
Phil says, "And now ladies and gentlemen, the '' man in showbiz, Pigpen!"
Seemingly they couldn't find their way into Untitled Post Eyes Jam
Weir says, "Polka time, ladies and gentleman. It's time to do the polka.

Lesh says, “Excuse me but we appreciate that there are some rules that apparently you can’t climb over this railing down here. But I think we can all appreciate it if the security folks would do their job with just a little less zeal.  Weir says, “And if the PA folks did their job with a little less squeal.”  Lesh says, “He’s a poet on his toes and it shows.”

Weir says, “As you can readily see one of our highly trained and expert crack equipment crew is taking care of Mickey’s drums which were not just exactly perfect. We are going to take a moment to get everything just exactly perfect.  Hart says, “We’re perfect. We’re exactly perfect.”  Weir says, “Mickey has informed me we are exactly perfect now we can proceed.”  Garcia mentions off mic “moving myself out claustrophobic.”  Weir says, “Meanwhile Jerry is improving his situation over here as well.”  Garcia, “I’m trying to make it as fucked up as possible. I’m not into that perfection shit. It’s almost perfectly fucked. Now where were we?”
At 13:46 into Love Light they shift into a blues riff resembling the beginning of Hand Me Down My Walkin Cane, then slip back into Turn On Your Love Light 34 seconds later.
Drummer's do a scat for 15 seconds
Weir says, "Candy, can we have a different light for the drummers. I don't want to be the same color as the drummers."
Weir, "This stage is filled with flotsam, you don't know.
Whistle Opening - Ever since she had a sex change!
Without Jerry, Phil doing the "passive aggressive"
Afterwards, Weir says, Weir "I want to thank the Oakland A's for making this afternoon possible...by losing."
a jam near the end worth denotiing
Prior to song Weir says, "so on the count of 3 everyone say Happy Birthday, Brentski. 1..2..3!"
starts with a False Start - off key 00:21
with Babatunde Olatunji and Sikiru Adepoju on percussion
with Babatunde Olatunji and Sikiru Adepoju on percussion
Garcia continually plays the opening of Comes A Time
21 beat false start: Weir says, "wait a minute. We got to teach our drummer how to count til 20." 5 beat
'a fuckin' shame' get back truckin' on 12 times
Weir says, "And now from our album, 'A Touch of Grey - the hit single."
At the 4:49 mark Phil cues an improv
At the 5:40 mark Phil cues the PITB jam
Weir plays his China Cat riff
No bass Intro. Weir voice has sound effects. Sings first verse without drums.
Weir says, "Of course now, we're gonna welcome back Bruce." And Jerry added, "We don't let just anybody sit in on the accordion!"
Lesh says "Ladies and Gentleman, Bruce Hornsby on the accordion!" Weir says, "Say 'thank you Bruce'".
Weir sings first verse with sparse drums
Lyric flub "Drown in your troubles and get to the store."

Before encore, “Hey everybody, I think what we just heard tonight was the Grateful Dead in St. Louis They know they are on their way home and they are very, very happy about it. They’ve been playing encores all along this tour and they probably do another one tonight. So if we let them know to come back. They’ll come back I’m sure of that.”
10 beats; with Mathew Kelly on Harmonica
Get Back Truckin' On: 3 times with scream on 4th measure.
At end of song Weir says, "Done Already"
Weir says, "You people are gonna get real flat and bugged eyed real quick."
Whistle Blowing opening; Get Back Truckin' On:  7 times Weir quips, "That's true" after 'sometimes I can barley see"
At end of song Weir says, "And I mean it."
Garcia botched opening. They restarted it again.
Brent plays La Bamba at the start
Mack The Knife played during technical difficulties. "We will work that up for next time."
Phil goes into Playing In The Band.
great, great transition into FG Jam
Afterwards Weir says, "Thank you. And now for our next number we're going to do a tune on death and destruction.
Garcia puts on a distortion pedal
Phil says, "Thanks a billion, folks! See you next year!"
Jerry loses the lyrics & compensates with extra solo sections.
Weir says, "Same old story and it's sad but true but if you don't know it I got news for you."
Afterwards Phil says, "OK,OK,OK,OK, now if y'all just shut up a second we'll play a quiet thing. Tender. Meaningful. Sympathetic. Heavy duty ballad in the key of b flat."
'ever since she went and had a sex change' Get Back Truckin' On - 11 times
after 3:57 Jerry continues on with just drums.
At the 6:46 moment, the power was shut off.
'flight of the sea birds..' not sung.
more a less an extended Eyes fade out with Phil & bobby eventually falling away leaving Garcia
Afterwards Weir says, "Now there's guy down there saying 'Let Mickey Sing' he's obviously never heard that. I mean, you can have it if you want it."
Lesh before show, "We were kinda hoping more of you would show up. I don't know. I heard there was a basketball game at the high school tonight so I can understand what's going on."
No encore. Phil tells audience their Soundman was arrested.
Lesh prior to encore, "Thank you. Actually we seem to have lost our drummers. Let's have a hand for our drummers, shall we?"
Weir, "This is gonna be a lot like work chasing this thing around tonight."
Weir, "Ya'll having a safe and sane fourth out there?

Lesh says, "Welcome America! Welcome Austin, Texas! Welcome everyone to Farm Aid TV. Than adds, "Looks like we got a tune up."   Weir, "America is at its backbone is an agrarian nation. Let's keep it turning."
Weir says, "Now we are going to do our little version of America's tune."
Jerry opens with the opening riff from 'Loser'.
Phil says, "The United States Blues" after song.
Weir says, "It isn't all that bad today because today is one of our equipment crew, Steve Parrish's birthday. So I want everybody on the count of three to say Happy Birthday Stevie."
with Drums; Donna screaming into the mic.

Lesh says prior to 'U.S. Blues', "Thanks a lot folks, it's nice to be back!"
includes a Got my mojo working vamp
